content:
Sure! Here's an example of a sidebar with the navlinks Home, About, and Contact:

```HTML
<aside class="sidebar">
  <nav class="sidebar-nav">
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
      <li><a href="#">About</a></li>
      <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
    </ul>
  </nav>
</aside>
```

And some CSS to style it:

```CSS
.sidebar {
  width: 200px;
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
  padding: 20px;
}

.sidebar-nav ul {
  list-style: none;
  padding: 0;
  margin: 0;
}

.sidebar-nav li {
  margin-bottom: 10px;
}

.sidebar-nav a {
  color: #333;
  font-weight: bold;
  text-decoration: none;
}

.sidebar-nav a:hover {
  color: blue;
  text-decoration: underline;
}
``` 

You can adjust the width and background-color of the sidebar to fit your website's style. And of course, don't forget to add your own links to the HREF attribute!
